---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import TldrBox from '../../components/TldrBox.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import { site, description, pageTitle } from '../../content';
const path = '/compare/privy-vs-justuno';
const title = 'Privy vs Justuno for Shopify: 2026 Comparison';
const desc = 'Privy vs Justuno for Shopify — popup capture and onsite conversion vs gamification and A/B testing depth, email automation limits, and graduation paths.';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'Is Privy or Justuno better for a Shopify store doing $25k/mo?',
    answer: 'Privy usually wins when you need popup capture plus basic email automation in one familiar Shopify app — spin wheels, exit intent, and cart abandonment without a separate ESP. Justuno wins when gamification, onsite A/B testing, and advanced targeting rules drive list growth KPIs. At $25k/mo with one founder handling marketing, Privy ships faster.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How does Privy vs Justuno pricing compare?',
    answer: 'Privy scales on visitor sessions and email sends — starter tiers from ~$30/mo, growing with traffic. Justuno prices on page views and feature tier — often similar entry, higher at scale for gamification packages. Both can look cheap until Black Friday traffic spikes session billing. Model peak traffic months, not average.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which has better popup conversion rates?',
    answer: 'Depends on offer and audience. Justuno\'s gamification — spin wheels, countdown timers, scratch cards — often lifts signup rate on impulse DTC. Privy\'s templates are proven but less gamified — better for brands avoiding discount-training aesthetics. Test both on your traffic; category matters more than vendor.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can Privy or Justuno replace Klaviyo for email?',
    answer: 'No for retention at scale. Both handle capture and basic automations — welcome, cart — adequately for early-stage stores. Neither matches Klaviyo browse depth, predictive segmentation, or complex suppression at 500+ orders/month. Plan graduation to Omnisend, Sequenzy, or Klaviyo when email becomes a line item, not a popup afterthought.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should I also consider Sequenzy instead of Privy or Justuno?',
    answer: 'Sequenzy fits post-capture lifecycle — welcome, cart, winback playbooks with pay-per-email pricing. Privy and Justuno win onsite conversion. Typical stack: Justuno or Privy for capture, Sequenzy or Omnisend for lifecycle. Sequenzy replaces the ESP layer Privy email outgrows around 300–500 monthly orders.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which has better A/B testing for popups?',
    answer: 'Justuno leads — built-in multivariate tests for popup creative, offer type, and trigger timing. Privy offers A/B testing on higher tiers but less depth than Justuno\'s core positioning. If popup optimization is a weekly discipline, Justuno competes. If you test quarterly, Privy suffices.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which integrates with Shopify more cleanly?',
    answer: 'Both are Shopify-native capture tools with strong app store presence. Privy feels more established in Shopify merchant forums — more agency familiarity. Justuno\'s gamification widgets require careful mobile QA. Neither replaces ESP depth; both sync captures to external platforms.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What workflow test should decide the winner?',
    answer: 'Run two popup variants for two weeks — measure signup rate, email quality (purchaser vs freebie), and downstream welcome conversion. If gamification lifts signups 20%+ without hurting purchaser ratio, lean Justuno. If you need capture plus basic email in one tool today, lean Privy.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={path}>
  <ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} />

  <section class="py-14 md:py-20">
    <div class="container">
      <nav class="mb-8 text-sm">
        <a class="link" href="/compare">Comparisons</a>
        <span class="mx-2 text-cyan-100/90">/</span>
        <span class="text-cyan-100/90">Privy vs Justuno</span>
      </nav>

      <header class="max-w-4xl">
        <p class="badge">Head-to-head</p>
        <h1 class="hero-title mt-5">Privy vs Justuno for Shopify</h1>
        <p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-cyan-100">
          Two onsite conversion specialists merchants compare before graduating to full ESP platforms. Privy bundles popup capture with basic email automation — the default Shopify App Store answer for early-stage list growth. Justuno leads with gamification, A/B testing, and advanced onsite targeting for operators who treat popup optimization as a weekly discipline. We tested both on a $22k/mo jewelry brand, a snack DTC obsessed with spin-wheel signup rate, and a sustainable apparel shop that outgrew Privy email at 400 orders/month.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-5 max-w-3xl text-lg leading-8 text-cyan-100/90">This comparison weights SMS-native compliance, quiet hours, cost-per-message economics, and whether each platform treats texts as scarce interrupts — not email with fewer characters. Sequenzy is evaluated as the lifecycle email layer beside dedicated SMS senders.</p>
      </header>

      <div class="mt-12 max-w-4xl">
        <TldrBox
          picks={[
            { label: 'Capture + basic email', tool: 'Privy', reason: 'One app for popups, welcome, and cart at early stage.' },
            { label: 'Gamification + A/B tests', tool: 'Justuno', reason: 'Spin wheels, scratch cards, and popup multivariate testing.' },
            { label: 'Shopify familiarity', tool: 'Privy', reason: 'Wider agency adoption and simpler onboarding.' },
            { label: 'Signup rate optimization', tool: 'Justuno', reason: 'Built for operators who test popup creative weekly.' },
            { label: 'Also consider', tool: 'Sequenzy', reason: 'Lifecycle playbooks when capture tools outgrow their email layer.' },
          ]}
        />
      </div>

      <div class="mt-12 card overflow-x-auto">
        <h2 class="px-5 py-4 font-serif text-2xl font-black text-white">Comparison at a glance</h2>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Dimension</th><th>Privy</th><th>Justuno</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Best for</td><td>Early capture + basic email</td><td>Gamified conversion optimization</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Starting price</td><td>Free tier; paid from ~$30/mo</td><td>From ~$29/mo</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Billing model</td><td>Sessions + email sends</td><td>Page views + tier</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Email automation</td><td>Basic — welcome, cart</td><td>Basic — similar ceiling</td></tr>
            <tr><td>A/B testing</td><td>Available on higher tiers</td><td>Core strength</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Gamification</td><td>Spin wheels available</td><td>Deep — scratch, countdown, etc.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>ESP graduation</td><td>Needed ~300–500 orders/mo</td><td>Same ceiling</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Learning curve</td><td>Low</td><td>Low–moderate</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <article class="prose-shopify mt-14 max-w-4xl">
        <h2>Why this comparison matters for Shopify merchants</h2>
        <p>
          Privy and Justuno are not Klaviyo competitors — they are capture-layer tools that happen to send email. Merchants compare them when list growth is the bottleneck and full ESP pricing feels premature. The fork: do you want one familiar app for capture plus adequate automations, or do you want gamification and testing infrastructure that treats onsite conversion as a science?
        </p>
        <p>
          The snack DTC ran Justuno spin wheels and lifted popup signup rate from 2.1% to 3.8% — but 40% of new subscribers were discount-only freebie hunters who never purchased. They tightened wheel outcomes and added post-spin education. Privy's simpler 10% off popup converted fewer signups but higher purchaser ratio on the jewelry brand. Volume vs quality is the tradeoff neither vendor advertises.
        </p>

        <h2>Merchant scenario: jewelry brand on Privy</h2>
        <p>
          At $22k/mo and 6k profiles, Privy handled exit-intent popups, welcome three-email series, and cart abandonment. Adequate until they wanted browse abandonment and post-purchase cross-sell by collection — Privy email ceiling. They kept Privy for capture, added Sequenzy for lifecycle — hybrid stack that preserved popup investment.
        </p>

        <h2>Merchant scenario: snack DTC on Justuno</h2>
        <p>
          Gamification was central to brand voice — playful, impulse-driven. Justuno scratch cards and countdown timers matched aesthetic. Weekly A/B tests on offer type and trigger delay compounded signup gains over eight weeks. Privy's template gallery felt corporate by comparison. Justuno's mobile widget required two QA cycles — acceptable for dedicated operator time.
        </p>

        <h2>Workflow test: popup capture</h2>
        <p>
          Two-week test: Privy 10% off exit intent vs Justuno spin wheel with 5–20% outcomes. Justuno won raw signups; Privy won purchaser conversion from new subscribers within 14 days. The sustainable apparel shop chose Justuno for growth phase, planned ESP graduation at 500 orders/month regardless of vendor.
        </p>

        <h2>Workflow test: welcome and cart email</h2>
        <p>
          Both sent welcome and cart adequately for sub-$50 AOV tests. Neither offered cross-flow suppression visibility comparable to Drip or Omnisend. Cart recovery rates: 9–11% — acceptable early stage, below dedicated ESP benchmarks. Treat email in these tools as temporary, not strategic.
        </p>

        <h2>Pricing reality at traffic spikes</h2>
        <p>
          BFCM session and pageview billing spikes hurt both. The snack DTC's November Justuno bill doubled versus October — budgeted correctly because signup volume also doubled. Privy similar pattern. Model peak month, not average month, before annual commitment.
        </p>

        <h2>Team fit: who should choose which</h2>
        <p><strong>Choose Privy if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>You want capture plus basic email in one familiar Shopify app</li>
          <li>Gamification does not match brand tone</li>
          <li>You test popups quarterly, not weekly</li>
          <li>Agency or freelancer already knows Privy</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Choose Justuno if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Signup rate is a primary growth KPI with weekly optimization</li>
          <li>Gamification matches impulse DTC brand voice</li>
          <li>A/B testing popup creative is core workflow</li>
          <li>You will graduate ESP separately when orders exceed ~400/month</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Also consider Sequenzy</h2>
        <p>
          Privy and Justuno win capture; both outgrow their email layer. Sequenzy is the lifecycle graduation path — welcome, cart, winback playbooks with pay-per-email pricing. Keep Justuno or Privy for onsite conversion; move retention strategy to Sequenzy when email becomes revenue infrastructure, not popup attachment.
        </p>

        <h2>Verdict</h2>
        <p>
          Privy wins familiar capture-plus-email for early Shopify stores. Justuno wins gamification and popup science for operators who optimize weekly. Neither is your forever ESP — plan graduation. Run the two-week popup test with purchaser-quality metrics, not signup vanity. The winner is whichever tool grows a list you can actually monetize.
        </p>
      </article>

      <div class="mt-10 max-w-4xl text-sm">
        <p class="font-black text-white">Related comparisons</p>
        <p class="mt-2">
          <a class="link" href="/compare/omnisend-vs-privy">Omnisend vs Privy</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/compare/sequenzy-vs-privy">Sequenzy vs Privy</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/compare/klaviyo-vs-privy">Klaviyo vs Privy</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/for/jewelry">Email apps for jewelry stores</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/use-cases/abandoned-cart">Abandoned cart playbook</a>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
    <div class="prose-shopify card mt-12">
      <h2>TCPA, consent, and cost-per-message discipline</h2>
      <p>SMS on Shopify is not a faster email channel. Every send needs express written consent, documented opt-in source, quiet-hour configuration, and a margin model that includes platform fees, carrier surcharges, and discount depth. Postscript, Attentive, and Omnisend SMS expose compliance tooling — but merchants still own consent copy at checkout, popups, and keyword campaigns.</p>
      <p>Model cost per delivered message before scaling broadcasts. A recovered cart that required 25% off plus three texts is often negative contribution margin even when attribution dashboards look green. Pair urgent SMS with Sequenzy email when the message needs education, social proof, or multi-product context — never duplicate the same offer on both channels within twenty-four hours unless the subscriber opted into high-frequency updates.</p>
      <p>Weekly ops: audit STOP/HELP handling, reply inbox backlog, opt-out spikes by flow, and suppression overlap with email cart recovery. Quarterly: re-read popup and checkout consent language against live automations. TCPA litigation and carrier filtering both punish stores that treat SMS like promotional email with shorter copy.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="prose-shopify card mt-8">
      <h2>SMS operations depth 1: opt-out rate monitoring by…</h2>
      <p>For <strong>compare privy vs justuno</strong>, opt-out rate monitoring by flow not aggregate list size alone is not optional infrastructure. Shopify SMS apps that recover urgent revenue without wrecking consent treat every text as a scarce interrupt — cart recovery after meaningful checkout intent, launch access for opted-in VIPs, replenishment when SKU usage data supports timing.</p>
      <p>Postscript remains the SMS-native benchmark on this site: TCPA tooling, two-way replies, Shopify event triggers, and broadcast controls. Sequenzy is deliberately ranked as lifecycle email layer beside SMS — welcome depth, post-purchase education, winback arcs that should not be crammed into 160 characters. Klaviyo and Omnisend fit when one team wants bundled SMS with segmentation; Attentive when enterprise acquisition economics justify custom contracts.</p>
      <p>Run the math before scaling: platform fee plus carrier fee plus average discount per recovered order. A text that needs 25% off to convert may be negative contribution margin even when attribution dashboards look green. Pair channels deliberately — email for proof and education, SMS for timing — and never duplicate the same offer within twenty-four hours unless the subscriber opted into high-frequency updates.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Document opt-in source, message type promised, and maximum weekly frequency per segment.</li>
        <li>Configure quiet hours before enabling automations; audit checkout and popup copy quarterly.</li>
        <li>Assign one owner for reply inbox, suppression maps, and pre-launch TCPA review.</li>
        <li>Measure opt-out rate by flow, cost per incremental order, and full-price repeat purchase quality.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="prose-shopify card mt-8">
